title_sort: w. a. jellison to walt whitman, 9 march 1864
title: W. A. Jellison to Walt Whitman, 9 March 1864
text: Dear Uncle WalterYou will doubtless be Somewhat Surprised to learn that I am in Washington but here I am and will try and give you a few details of my Adventures Since I left Armory Square Well I went to Camp Destribution[Distribution] well after we got thare[there] the doctor Sent word around for all the wounded men to be Examined he Sent me to Angaer General Hospital then I was Examined thare[there] by the Board and Ordered to be Sent to Washington what they will do with me now is more than I can tell thare[there] now haint[ain't] I done well Oh! I would like to see you verry[very] much for I like Uncle Walter verry[very] much now dont[don't] think I am trying to play the flatterer for I haint[ain't] no Such a person now I want you to come up and See me Just as soon as you can and the first pass I can get I am coming to see you for I have got lots to tell you that would be Imposible[impossible] to write please drop me a note by Return mail in the meantime I am yours Etc. W. A. Jellison to Walt Whitman, 9 March 1864
